The paper discusses a method to monitor and record scientists' working timetable by analyzing their downloads of scientific papers. This involves data collection and analysis, which falls under the category of computational science (cs.CY). The paper also mentions the use of Springer, which is a publisher of scientific papers, indicating a focus on digital libraries (cs.DL). The analysis of scientists' working habits involves information retrieval (cs.IR) and data mining (cs.SI). Finally, the paper discusses the impact of work on weekends and overnight work, which relates to human-computer interaction (cs.HC) and the study of work-life balance.
